## Brief table of Laplace Transforms {.scrollable .smaller}

| $$f(t)$$||$$F(s)$$| |
|------|---|------|-----|
|$$1$$||$$\frac{1}{s}$$|$$s>0$$|
|$$e^{at}$$||$$\frac{1}{s-a}$$|$$s>a$$|
|$$t^n$$||$$\frac{n!}{s^{n+1}}$$|$$s>0,\quad n\in \mathbb{N}$$|
|$$\sin kt$$||$$\frac{k}{s^2+k^2}$$|$$s>0$$|
|$$\cos kt$$||$$\frac{s}{s^2+k^2}$$|$$s>0$$|
|$$e^{at}t^n$$||$$\frac{n!}{(s-a)^{n+1}}$$|$$s>0,\quad n\in \mathbb{N}$$|
|$$e^{at}\sin kt$$||$$\frac{k}{(s-a)^2+k^2}$$|$$s>a$$|
|$$e^{at}\cos kt$$||$$\frac{s-a}{(s-a)^2+k^2}$$|$$s>a$$|


## Theorem for Translation
::: callout-note

::: {#thm-transl}
## Translation

$$\boxed{\mathscr{L}\{e^{at}f(t)\}=F(s-a)}$$ where $F(s)=\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}$
:::

## proof {.scrollable}

$$\mathscr{L}\{e^{at}f(t)\}=\int_0^\infty e^{-st}e^{at}f(t)\,dt$$
$$=\int_0^\infty e^{-(s-a)t}f(t)\,dt$$

$$=F(s-a)$$

$$\square$$
:::

### Example {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-tip}
## Example

$$\mathscr{L}\{e^{-2t}t^3\}=$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution:


$$\mathscr{L}\{e^{-2t}t^3\}=\mathscr{L}\{t^3\}\Big|_{s\rightarrow s-(-2)}$$
Evaluate and then Shift:

$$=\frac{3!}{s^4}\Big|_{s\rightarrow s+2}$$
$$=\frac{3!}{(s+2)^4}$$

:::
:::

## $f(t)$ be of exponential order. {.scrollable}

:::{.callout-note}
## Definition

A function $f(t)$ is said to be `of exponential order` if $\exists M,C,T>0$ such that
$$|f(t)|\leq Me^{ct},\qquad \forall t\geq T$$

```{r, echo=FALSE}
#t <- seq(-3,5,length.out=200)
y <- function(t) {sin(t)+t^2.1*(sin(10*t))+5*sin(30*t)}
yexp1 <- function(t) {exp(t/1.5)}
yexp2 <- function(t) {-exp(t/1.5)}
curve(y, from =-0, to =7, col="black", lwd=2, n=2000, ylab="",xlab="t")
curve(yexp1, from =-0, to =7, col="blue", lwd=2, n=200, add = TRUE)
curve(yexp2, from =-0, to =7, col="blue", lwd=2, n=200, add = TRUE)
abline(v=4.4, col=2, lwd=3, lty=3)
text(x = 4.15, y = -40, label = "t=T")
text(x = 5.0, y = -39, label = expression(-Me^{ct}))
text(x = 5.0, y = 39, label = expression(Me^{ct}))
#mtext("of exponential order", side = 3, line = -3, outer = TRUE)
#curve(t,,type = "l",ylim = c(-50,50), col="blue", lwd=2, add = TRUE)
```
:::

## $f(t)$ be a piecewise continuous. {.scrollable}

:::{.callout-note}
## Definition

A function $f(t)$ is a `piecewise continuous` for $t\geq 0$ if all of the following are true.

1. There are a finite number of discontinuities at $0=t_0<t_1<\cdots<t_k$
2. $f(t)$ is continuous on $\{(0,t_1),(t_1,t_2),\cdots,(t_k,\infty)\}$
3. $|f(t)|<M\quad\forall t$ for some $M$.

```{r,echo=FALSE}
#t <- seq(-3,5,length.out=200)
y1 <- function(t) {t*sin(t)+2}
y2 <- function(t) {sin(2*t)+5}
y3 <- function(t) {-(t-7)^2+2}
y4 <- function(t) {10*exp(-(t-9)^2/9)+2}
plot(c(0,3,6,8),c(2,4.8,1,11),xlim = c(0,15),ylim = c(0,13), pch = 16, ylab="f(t)",xlab="t", cex=1.5, col="blue",xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n", frame.plot = 1)
curve(y1, from =0, to =3, col="black", lwd=2, n=2000, ylab="",xlab="", xlim = c(0,15),ylim = c(0,13),add = TRUE,xaxt = "n",xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
